II. Emmoxs

The earliest editions (J ohannes de Amerbach, 1493 ; Erasmus, 1528, 1569) possess only a bibliographical in— terest. The editors of the Louvain edition of the complete works of Augustine (1576) added 29 new letters, some of which are found also as anecdota in the Supplementum to Augustine by Hieronymus Vignier (Paris, 1654—1655). Α separate edition of the Letters was given in 1668 by L. F. Reinhart, who added seven more to the corpus. But an epoch-making recension and re-arranging appeared just a hundred years later, in the edition of the complete works prepared by the Benedictines of St. Maur. They added 16 letters, making a total of 270, of which number 53 were addressed to Augustine, the remainder being written by him, sometimes in conjunction with others.
